Actually, there's a less hacky way of accomplishing this now. `authenticate` supports an `interactive` option:
http://coffeedoc.info/github/dropbox/dropbox-js/master/classes/Dropbox/Client.html#authenticate-instance

If you use this option, your callback must figure out if cached credentials were used or not. `isAuthenticated` can help.
http://coffeedoc.info/github/dropbox/dropbox-js/master/classes/Dropbox/Client.html#isAuthenticated-instance

Here is how you'd put these together.

``` javascript
// Try to use cached credentials.
client.authenticate({interactive: false}, function(error, client) {
  if (error) {
    return handleError(error);
  }
  if (client.isAuthenticated() {
    // Cached credentials.
    doSomethingCool();
  } else {
    // show and set up the "Sign into Dropbox" button
    var button = document.querySelector("#signin-button");
    button.setAttribute("class", "visible");
    button.addEventListener("click", function() {
      // Regular authentication.
      client.authenticate(function(error, client) {
        if (error) {
          return handleError(error);
        }
        doSomethingCool();
      });
    });
  }
});
```

