AngularJS, Backbone, etc. should learn to deal with this situation. A part of the OAuth 2 specification (implicit grant) mandates that the access token info is passed in the URL fragment, using the same URL encoding that the Redirect driver is using above.

So, once the Dropbox API server supports OAuth 2, we'll end up in this situation again.

When you redirect to your external endpoint, dropbox also sends the tokens as part of the URL.
The `Dropbox.Drivers.Popup.oauthReceiver();` code:

```
Popup.oauthReceiver = function() {
      return window.addEventListener('load', function() {
        var frameError, ieError, opener;

        opener = window.opener;
        if (window.parent !== window.top) {
          opener || (opener = window.parent);
        }
        if (opener) {
          try {
            opener.postMessage(window.location.href, '*');
          } catch (_error) {
            ieError = _error;
          }
          try {
            opener.Dropbox.Drivers.Popup.onMessage.dispatch(window.location.href);
          } catch (_error) {
            frameError = _error;
          }
        }
        return window.close();
      });
    };
```

This code access your original window that opened the pop-up and sends it a message with `window.location.href`. That variable has the tokens and completes the auth flow. After that the credentials are stored using `BrowserBase.prototype.storeCredentials` I believe.

